{
  "texts": [
    "Furthermore, the relatively small size of the field of computational paleontology exacerbates these challenges (Cope et al. 2012, Rayfield 2007; Bakker et al. 2020).",
    "Another key challenge is the broad variability in fossil preservation, with fossils found in conditions ranging from nearly intact (with soft tissues preserved even in some ancient examples (Jiang et al. 2022; Fabbri et al. 2020)) to heavily eroded and/or fragmented.",
    "This variability leads to inconsistencies in visual data, posing a substantial obstacle for DL models.",
    "Such inconsistencies affect not just identification but also the accuracy of classification and segmentation tasks (Kidwell and Holland 2002; Hadly 1999; Seilacher 1978; Ching et al. 2018).",
    "Additionally, the diversity and subtly varying morphology of fossils, coupled with varied levels of intra-and inter-specific variation in the living communities they represent, present a challenge for current DL models, demanding heightened sensitivity to minor morphological and phylogenetically sensitive species delineation (Buatois et al. 2017; Kidwell et al. 1986; Lloyd et al. 2012)."
  ]
}